name: BLM Camping-
description: Free primitive camping located next to major freeway but the noise is not overwhelming.

name: Pump Station BLM
description: Very spacious, clean, free dry camping spaces.

name: Grand Canyon Trail Rides
description: This marker location is a business. Do not go there.  It's only being used to mark the forest road (328) that has camping spots.

name: Long Jim Loop Camping
description: Simple forested campground in Grand Canyon National Park offering tent & RV sites.

name: BLM Sacred White Shell Mountain
description: Free dry camping near Great Sand Dunes NP.

name: Parking Lot for Chutes & Ladders
description: Designated camping spots near Mesa Verde NP. Nearby is a rest stop with flushing toilets.

name: Lake DeWeese
description: Reflecting magnificent peaks, DeWeese Reservoir State Wildlife Area backs up behind an impressive dam at the head of Grape Creek Canyon, just a half-dozen miles north of Westcliffe. The wildlife area encompasses 2,336 acres, with the reservoir covering 208.

name: Campo Community Center
description: Free RV parking at the park.

name: Stillwater Pass
description: Free dispersed camping, near Grand Lake and Stillwater campground.

name: Williams Fork Reservoir Campground
description: Camping is allowed from April 1 through Nov. 30 in designated areas.

name: Gordon Gulch Dispersed Camping Area, CO
description: There are 15 numbered, designated campsites scattered along the road system within 1.5 miles east of Highway 72. Camping is permitted in designated sites only.

name: Danbory Rest Area
description: Rest areas and service plazas

name: Biden Welcome Center
description: Great welcome center. Lots of bathroom stalls.

name: Midway Campground
description: Campground near Everglades NP. Next to highway but is quiet at night.

name: Spillway Campground
description: The Spillway Campground is a small campground with 3 campsites along Anderson Ranch Reservoir.  The reservoir is a popular destination for fishing, boating, waterskiing and riding personal watercraft.

name: Little Camas Reservoir Campground
description: Free dispersed camping with pit toilets.

name: Jacks Creek Campground
description: An open access site with no amenities, has pit toilets.

name: Tower Rock Campground, Shawnee National Forest
description: Located along the banks of the Ohio River, Tower Rock Campground offers beautiful scenery and close proximity to water activities like fishing and boating.

name: Turkey Bayou
description: Located in Oakwood Bottoms, Turkey Bayou Campground is a great location outdoor activities including waterfowl hunting, deer hunting, trapping, fishing, nature watching and bird watching.

name: Dutchman Lake
description: A beautiful undeveloped lake in Shawnee Forest, has a boat ramp,  good place to fish or just sit quietly and meditate.

name: Dunewood Campground
description: Campground consists of two loops containing 66 camp-sites (53 conventional drive-in sites and 13 walk/carry-in sites).

name: Concannon Wildlife Area
description: The area offers a large variety of recreational opportunities to the visitors. Primitive camping is allowed in an area that has ADA restrooms, an ADA courtesy dock, and a boat ramp.

name: Bourbon State Fishing Lake
description: This lake is a little off the beaten path but an amazing place to camp. Camping is free and they have a water spout and a pit bathroom available.

name: Kiowa County State Lake
description: Free camping in a park with a lake inside a city. It can get noisy because of traffic and trains.

name: Bullitt County Welcome Center Southbound
description: Unbelievably clean and safe rest area.

name: SB Horse Cave Rest Area
description: Clean restrooms. Ample parking. Safe.

name: Little Lick Campground
description: Little Lick Horse Camp is a primitive equestrian campground with four family camping areas and two double campsites located on a long ridgetop in the southeast corner of Pulaski County.

name: Salem Lake
description: There is free 2 day camping. Saw some GIANT fish in the lake.

name: Dogwood Campground
description: Easy access to the district and spring dogwood blooms make this campground a popular destination for visitors who want to cover the whole district. Camping (16 drive-in units accessible to small RV's and trailers), drinking water, and sanitary facilities (flush toilets). Trash disposal available.

name: Sam Forse Collins Recreation Area
description: This park has group facilities, playground equipment, a boat ramp, picnic tables, a wheelchair-accessible fishing pier, and restrooms. There are no usage fees.

name: Ahtus Melder Campground
description: A very peaceful unique free camping area on what remains of a 1940s military base.

name: Camping Area
description: Nice camping area. Quiet and peaceful. Nice shade. Clean restroom.

name: Trout Brook Campsites
description: It is free. First come first serve. Wilderness camp site. You may need to call the state and get a fire permit.

name: Maine’s Bureau of Parks and Lands Primative Campground
description: Gorgeous scenery and perfect for paddling. A good place to visit for a day or to camp with family or friends.

name: Swains Lock Hiker/Biker Campsite
description: Potable water may not be available at each campsite. Water is treated with iodine. Please plan to have water purification tablets with you.

name: Sulak Campground
description: This site is primarily used by anglers, hunters and families for camping.

name: Sparrow Rapids Campground
description: This campgrouind has six campsites that can accomodate tents, trailers, and motor homes. It is a limited service campground.

name: French Farm Lake
description: Last lake in the Lower Peninsula before you get to the bridge and in fact, you can see the Mackinac Bridge from the south side of the lake.

name: Hovey Lake Campground
description: This isolated, quiet, family type camping area is located on the east side of Hovey Lake. It is a good place for canoeing, bird watching or just enjoying nature surroundings. There are four campsites, each with a table and fire ring. Toilets and drinking water are available.

name: Echo Lake Campground
description: Echo Lake is located on the west end of the Echo Trail, a remote country road that traverses through the heart of the Western Superior National Forest.

name: Ash River Campground
description: A perfectly fine car camping spot. Just the space to pull in, a tent pad, fire ring & pit toilets. Nothing fancy.

name: Wooden Frog Campground and Day Use Area
description: Located near Voyageurs National Park and the Kabetogama Visitor Center, this campground offers a swimming beach, hiking trail, and scenic picnic area on a pine-covered point on Lake Kabetogama.

name: Big Rice Lake Rustic Campground
description: The area offers a drive-in rustic campground with 3 campsites, duck hunting, a boat launch for small boats and some fishing.

name: Poplar River Rustic Campground
description: Several of the sites have access directly to the river, so stream fishing for trout can be done right from your campsite!

name: Six Mile Campground
description: Beautiful, right on the lake, spots have plenty of room to pull in/back out. No hook-ups.

name: Davis Bayou Campground
description: Davis Bayou Campground is located east of downtown Ocean Springs, Mississippi, and is a part of Gulf Islands National Seashore.

name: Prairie Home Conservation Area
description: Prairie Home Conservation Area, located in eastern Cooper County, is an upland area with a mix of oldfields, small cropfields, grasslands, and woodlands.

name: Schell-Osage Conservation Area
description: Schell-Osage Conservation Area and the Osage River, which forms the area's north boundary, derive their names from the Osage Indians that once inhabited the area.

name: Lead Mine Conservation Area
description: Visitors will find five primitive camping areas. The main campground has 50 sites and is the only location of a privy. No other facilities are provided in any other camping areas. Camping is all on a first come-first served basis with no permit or reservation required.

name: Bar-K Wrangler Campsite
description: Whether you choose one of the designated sites or decide to spread out in the big field across the road you’ll have plenty of room for yourself and your horse when you visit.

name: Berryman Campground
description: With just 8 individual campsites and a picnic shelter, it is enjoyed by campers, picnickers, mountain bikers, equestrians, and hikers.

name: Robert E. Talbot Conservation Area
description: Along with high quality upland habitat, visitors will find several miles of multiuse trails that are open to hiking, biking, and horseback riding. Camping is allowed only in the spot designated on the area map. No facilities are provided at the campground. The campground is best suited for tents or small travel trailers/RVs.

name: Bismarck Camp Ground
description: The Department provides a boat ramp, parking areas, and disabled accessible facilities, including a fishing jetty.

name: Patrick Bridge Access Campground
description: The Patrick Bridge Access is an area with 161 acres that provide fishing access and recreational opportunities on the North Fork of the White River.

name: Clark Memorial Campground
description: This is an open, sunny site in the canyon bottom along the river. There is a forest nearby and fishing opportunities in the Thompson River.

name: Copper King Campground
description: A picnic table and fire ring is available at each campsite. The campground road is not suitable for long vehicles or trailers. The group site is available on a first-come, first-served basis.

name: Oliver Reservoir Campground
description: 48 campsites with fire pits plus overflow sites without fire pits are available.

name: Sacramento Pass BLM Campground
description: Other amenities include picnic tables, grills, shade structures, trash cans and restrooms. No potable water. Camping available in 10 sites with a 14-day limit.

name: Gale River Campground
description: Nice dispersed first come first serve camping area. Sites are very spaced out almost like a quarter of a mile between each site. The sites each have a fire ring.

name: Oasis State Park
description: Oasis State Park is set among cottonwood trees, shifting sand dunes, and a small fishing lake. Although fishing is the park’s main draw, it also has several hiking trails, a peaceful and shady campground, and an abundance of birds.

name: Rockhound State Park
description: The rugged slopes of the Little Florida Mountains are the setting for this park, which boasts trails, unique geology, wildflower displays, and a peaceful campground.

name: Cave Campground
description: Fort Stanton Cave Campground features several shelters, tables and fire rings, as well as a vault toilet. All sites are dry and on a first-come, first-served basis.

name: Joe Skeen Campground
description: Free campground with shaded picnic tables, very clean, theres a pit toilet nearby and lots of great exploring to do in the conservation area, walked right from the campsite into a great hike.

name: Parks Ranch Cave System
description: A gypsum cave with over four miles of mapped passage and twenty different entrances, it is the longest gypsum cave on public land in the United States.

name: Chosa Campground
description: Camping is free and the camping limit is 14 days. The entire area is a large, square, gravel parking lot which makes it easy for leveling.

name: Upper Karr Recreation Area
description: Upper Karr Canyon Campground is located off of NM6563 (the Sunspot Scenic Byway) and has a 200 person capacity. There are 2 fire rings, 1 toilet, and garbage depositories are provided. RVs limited to 16'.

name: Sunset Reef Campground
description: The Sunset Reef Campground, located off the Washington Ranch Road, is a reclaimed well pad with 11 developed campsites; five RV spaces and six tent sites. Each site has a covered picnic table and grill for your camping convenience with a vault toilet on site. Visitors can dry camp in the area for a maximum of five nights for free.

name: Angel Peak Campground
description: 9 tent camping sites, each with picnic tables on a concrete pad, gravel pathways, and fire grates.

name: 909/Taconic Hereford Trail Parking
description: Download map; one primitive site.

name: Allaben Campground
description: The Allaben parcel is largely undeveloped forest with primitive campsites. The Rochester Hollow area contains ruins of a former estate and a spruce plantation that is the John Burroughs Memorial Forest. Download map from their site.

name: Kelly Hollow Trail
description: Easy, beautiful hike. Cleanest lean-to and camp area.

name: Woodhull Mountain Trail Parking
description: Beautiful forest and nice primitive camping sites with access to Woodhull Lake.

name: Seneca One Stop
description: They offer showers.

name: East Otto State Forest Campground
description: East Otto State Forest covers 1,354 acres. The most common recreational use of this area is hunting and camping.

name: Moose River Plains Wild Forest
description: The area features more than 100 primitive roadside campsites, miles of marked trails and numerous lakes and ponds.

name: Walter Pratt Memorial park
description: Tall pine trees, sand dune features, wetlands areas in addition to the pond. Don't go there if you're expecting modern amenities.

name: Little Green Pond Campground
description: Huge and ideal flat ground and space for pitching tents.  It doesn't feel at all like you are crowded in with other people.

name: Blueberry Patch Campground
description: There are nine campsites available. Each has a fire pit, a tent pad, a picnic table, and parking for up to two cars. This campground is designed for tents or small campers under 24 feet long. Some of the picnic tables are handicap accessible. There are two handicap accessible vault toilets.

name: Sugar Hill Fire Tower
description: The 9,085-acre Sugar Hill State Forest has the multiple-use Six Nations Trail System, the Finger Lakes Hiking Trail, the Sugar Hill Recreation Area including the Sugar Hill Fire Tower, and five lean-tos.

name: Sanford Lake
description: Very rustic campsites. It is a dry campground. No outhouse, just a filthy portapotty.

name: Entrance to Sonyea State Forest
description: The 922-acre Sonyea State Forest offers a rustic experience with a limited amount of development. This forest shares a common boundary with Groveland Correctional Facility.

name: Yates Place Campground
description: Yates Place Camp was an old home site, but now serves as an attractive destination for tent camping. A vaul toilet, tables, and grills are available at the site.

name: Moon Lake Campground
description: Really nice place to camp for free. Gravel roads to get there but they were in pretty good condition.

name: Silver Springs Campground
description: Nestled in Silver Springs Park in the Northeast corner of Stow, it is one of only a few municipally-operated campgrounds in Ohio.

name: Annie Creek Sno-Park
description: Annie Creek Sno-Park is located 43 miles northwest of Klamath Falls, Oregon, near the Crater Lake National Park.

name: Lemolo Forebay 2
description: Free Camping. Has Restroom. 6 spots to choose from. Quiet and plenty fish to catch.

name: Thielsen Forest Camp
description: Thielsen Forest Camp is a free Forest Service campground that provides a great place to camp for travelers on a budget. This relatively small campground only contains 5 car/ tent sites, but it is often completely unused.

name: Toketee Lake Campground
description: This campground is popular for anglers and year-round visitors to the Umpqua National Forest. Toketee Lake is a reservoir because of a dam. With 33 campsites enjoy the serene views of Toketee Lake under the stars.

name: Thielsen View Campground
description: Few other sites in the Umpqua National Forest offer so much concentrated natural splendor. Visitors can simultaneously bask in the shadow of Mount Bailey and get an unforgettable view of Mount Thielsen from across Diamond Lake. Like its sister site across the lake, Thielsen View Campground is a perennial favorite among anglers.

name: Diamond Lake Campground
description: Diamond Lake Campground is nestled among conifer trees along the east shore of the mile-high Diamond Lake. This campground offers 51 lakeshore camping sites as well as 187 inshore sites.

name: Broken Arrow Campground
description: Set back from the shores of Diamond Lake, Broken Arrow Campground is nestled in lodgepole pine forest. This picturesque spot has 121 campsites and boasts views of both Mount Bailey and Mt. Thielsen.

name: MIll Creek Campground
description: Mill Creek Campground is adjacent to Mill Creek. The campground has opportunity for fishing and swimming.

name: Scott Creek Campground
description: This site lies off the beaten path and is an ideal camping destination if you want to relax in a serene and remote setting. A mix of conifers like lodgepole, ponderosa pines, and white firs shade the six campsites.

name: Clarion River Campground
description: Nice camp sites for car camping. But since they are first come, there's a good chance you're not going to get a sight to camp at. There are vault toilets.

name: Bear Mountain Fire Tower
description: Primitive camping along the road to this tower.

name: Sage Creek Campground
description: Experience Badlands National Park overnight in one of its two established campgrounds: Cedar Pass Campground and Sage Creek Campground.

name: Badlands Boondock Campspot
description: Free with amazing views of Badlands NP. It was pretty busy, but there are quite a few sites. Try to be there in the morning. First come, first served. Very good cell phone reception.

name: Buffalo Gap National Grassland
description: Beautifully peaceful night of camping just outside Badlands NP.

name: Hugh Glass State Lakeside Use Area
description: Great place to stay!  Fishing is right down the hill! Camping spots are spaced nicely.

name: Reva Gap Campground
description: A campground with 8 sites located in the Slim Buttes Unit near the Castles National Natural Landmark, one of two on the Sioux Ranger District.

name: Sandy Creek
description: Sandy Creek Park is located on the southeast side of B.A. Steinhagen Lake between the towns of Woodville and Jasper in southeast Texas.

name: South Holiday Park
description: Holiday Park campground is on the west side of Benbrook Lake in north central Texas and accessible from US Hwy 377.

name: East Fork Park
description: East Fork Campground, on the southern shores of Lavon Lake, is a popular escape for city dwellers in the Dallas, Texas area or for any visitors passing through the Northern Texas region.

name: Aspen Nature Trail
description: This is a location marker for camping on FR 048.

name: Cedar Mesa Campground
description: This primitive, no-fee campground has five (5) sites, each with a picnic table and fire grate. There is also a pit toilet, but no water is available. Usually two-wheel drive vehicles can access Cedar Mesa Campground, but sometimes the road requires high clearance.

name: Sawmill Hollow Campground
description: Previously a free to use area, as of May 2024 there is a fee to use this area now. Campground has a pit toilet in fairly good condition. 4 campsites with picnic tables and fire pits, with additional dispersed camping opportunities along the trail.

name: Mammoth Designated Dispersed Camping Area
description: Beautiful secluded spot for dispersed camping. Some designated spots are *right* on the creek. There is absolutely no cell service down there.

name: Yankee Designated Dispersed Camping Area
description: Yankee Meadows designated dispersed campground is situated in a beautiful valley near Yankee Meadows Reservoir.

name: Hurricane Cliffs Recreational Area BLM
description: Camping throughout Hurricane Cliffs is limited to 56 Designated Dispersed Sites that were implemented to protect the expansive views and scenic integrity of the area.

name: Red Canyon Boondock Camping
description: This is a great free camping area in Red Canyon.

name: Oak Grove Campground
description: There are free dispersed camping along the road leading to this campground.

name: Dixie National Forest Dispersed Camping Area
description: Free dispersed camping in Dixie National forest.

name: Camp Kelly Campground
description: This is a nice, remote spot in Southwestern Vermont.

name: Somerset Airfield
description: Year round free camping surrounded by a dense forest with a pristine River running through.

name: Bingo Brook
description: No amenities. Very close to roughing it. A few good trails to hike bring machete bushwhacking needed very grown in in many areas.

name: Little Fort Campground
description: Little Fort is a first-come-first-serve minimally developed recreation area located near the meadow that was once a rest stop for a stagecoach line.

name: Raccoon Canyon
description: Free campsites right between the dirt road and the creek. No facilities. Beautiful little valley.

name: Two Hatchets Camp Site
description: Beautiful little campsite near the creek. Road also near, a little close to other campsites but not within sight or hearing range.

name: Walnut Flats Campground
description: This small, primitive campground is well suited for tent camping but also accommodates small recreation vehicles. It has shaded sites clustered around a grassy opening surrounded by forest.

name: Oronoco Campground
description: Beautiful, secluded National Forest camping area. (Free and usable for 21 days) There are several sites by the river (with enough space for an RV) and a few in the field and woods.

name: Moody Boat Launch - Mile 13
description: Surrounded by a spectacular nature setting, sits the secluded Moody Boat Launch. Find pleasure in the convenient facility that allows one easy access to the South Fork of the Shenandoah River.

name: Sahara Creek DNR Horse Camp
description: Great horse camp well maintained and managed.

name: Bear Creek Campground
description: This 16-campsite campground is located along the Sol Duc River. Visitors to the campground can take a hiking trail to the river and fish along its banks. Amenities include a scenic overlook, two toilets. Campsites can accommodate up to a 30-foot trailer, though size may vary by site.

name: Hoh Oxbow Campground
description: Located near the Hoh River near the edge of the Olympic National Park, Hoh Oxbow Campground offers pristine camping among a dense, mossy forest of hemlock and fir. Facilities include eight campsites, toilet. Campsites can accommodate up to a 30-foot trailer, though size may vary by site.

name: Minnie Peterson Campground
description: Limited number of spaces. Must have a Discovery Pass. No services services (trash cans, water, electric) since it’s free. Limited number of sites. Sites are very spacious and private.

name: Folsom Farm Site
description: At BLM's Fishtrap Area, the historic Folsom Farm interpretive site demonstrates how the landscape was converted into small farms, ranches, and communities beginning in the late 1800's.

name: Meadow Creek Campground
description: This tent-only primitive campground located along the New River is only one mile from the Sandstone Visitor Center. It offers 17 tent sites in an open field. The railroad crossing can be dangerous for larger RVs and trailers. RV camping is prohibited.

name: Gauley Tailwaters Campground
description: The National Park Service offers primitive camping at Gauley Tailwaters, located just below Summersville Dam. From Route 19 at Mt. Nebo, take Route 129 west across the dam, then turn left at the river access sign. Bear right through the parking lot to the campsites. There are 18 drive-in sites for tents and RVs.

name: Potato River Falls Campground
description: It's free so most all the spots have tents set up that look like they've been there a while. There are about 8 spots.

name: Teton Reservoir BLM Campground
description: Set in the rolling sage grasslands of the Great Divide Basin, this reservoir becomes a watery oasis under the bright summer skies. Fishing for trout in the reservoir and surrounding streams is good; this is also a popular non-motorized water sports area. This is a free site with 5 campsites, vault toilets, boat ramp, and day use parking. Campsites have picnic tables, fire ring/grills, and parking spurs with no pull-throughs.

name: Warren Peak Lookout Tower
description: A location marker for camping opportunities along the road leading to the tower.

name: Dugway Campground
description: This is a free site with 5 campsites (1 pull-through, 4 spurs), group site, vault toilet, day use parking, picnic tables, fire rings/grills, and parking spur. The main attraction is the North Platte River for fishing and floating. No horses are allowed in the campground.

name: Grayrocks Reservoir
description: This area is beautiful and quiet. You can camp up to 5 days for free. They have dumpsters but no toilets. Nice area to fish or kayak.

name: 700c camp site
description: Large sites and spread out.

name: Ryan Park Campground
description: The campground is next to Barrett Creek in the Medicine Bow National Forest and features 49 campsites (13 RV pull-through sites) and 1 group campsite. Nearby are free dispersed camping in USFS land.
